Chill, dude.  He got them backwards is all.

I'm doing this from an article I read some time ago, since I haven't yet
played with shortcuts on Win95.

As I recall, all files on a Win95 hard drive have a stamp within them
which contains the precise millisecond of their creation.  A shortcut
refers not to a filename, but to that timestamp.  Thus, the original
can move and be renamed all you want, with no troubles.  I hope they've
tested the results of two objects having an identical timestamp, but the
odds of that are vanishingly small.

On the Mac, the alias refers to the full path name.  (Same with UNIX links.
I think that shadows on OS/2 also do this.)  Thus, moving the original
breaks the alias.  There are shareware utilities that make this easier
to fix, and there is a "Find Original" button in the Get Info box which
can be useful, but the Mac method has obvious weaknesses compared to
the Win95 version.  Of course, I've had very few problems with the Mac
method, and have been using it for years, but that does not mean that
the Mac method is as good.  In this case, it's not.

