medcalf@ppc5.svo.dfw.ibm.com (Jeff Medcalf (214) 280-5970 IBM SDO) wrote:

>As I recall, all files on a Win95 hard drive have a stamp within them
>which contains the precise millisecond of their creation.  A shortcut
>refers not to a filename, but to that timestamp.  Thus, the original
>can move and be renamed all you want, with no troubles.  I hope they've
>tested the results of two objects having an identical timestamp, but the
>odds of that are vanishingly small.

What happens when you duplicate a file, or option-drag a file to copy it
instead of moving it?  Is the creation timestamp the same on the copies,
or not?  If it is the same, the odds of an identical creation timestamp
can be quite large.

>On the Mac, the alias refers to the full path name.  (Same with UNIX
links.
>I think that shadows on OS/2 also do this.)  Thus, moving the original
>breaks the alias.  There are shareware utilities that make this easier
>to fix, and there is a "Find Original" button in the Get Info box which
>can be useful, but the Mac method has obvious weaknesses compared to
>the Win95 version.

Baloney.  Stick to what you know.  Every Macintosh file can be given a
unique file ID that sticks to the file even when it is moved to other
locations on disk.  Macintosh aliases primarily use this file ID
mechanism, although they also store information about the file's path,
volume, folder etc to track down the appropriate file in case the original
file has been deleted.

If you've *ever* worked with aliases on the Mac, you'd know that moving
the original file does *not* break the alias.  Neither does renaming any
folder in the file's path, renaming the volume, moving any folder in the
file's path, etc.  In addition, the MacOS will also find the appropriate
file if you duplicate the original, delete the original, and then rename
the copy to the same name as the original.

