ltchean@iss.nus.sg (Lim Thye Chean) writes:

>Jeff Medcalf (214) 280-5970 IBM SDO (medcalf@ppc5.svo.dfw.ibm.com) wrote:

>: You are correct that most of the time it won't matter.  It'll matter a
>: lot in there is a problem with your disk that corrupts the extended
>: filename info, and your scripts depend on the extended filename info.

>Currently, the programs that can cause those problems are the disk utilities.
>Windows 95 users should not rely on old disk utilities. (I am not into
>debating that whether this is right or wrong, just the fact)

Actually, WIn95 will protect itself from these programs. When you go
into SAM mode (or in a DOS window), if it detects an attempt to directly
access the disk, it will inform you that this is not allowed, and you
must type "LOCK" in order to allow the direct disk access, after warning
you that you could be wiping out all the LFNs.  So you will have to try
fairly hard to wipe out the LFNs - simply starting an old program won't
do it.

Also, there is a little application which can be used to change all the
LFNs to 8.3, and save the changes to a file, which can then be restored,
so if you just had to do something which would screw up all the LFNs,
you could use this utility to save a lot of headaches.

Note that if you go to install NT from in Win95, you must lock the drive
or the setup won't run - which is how I discovered all this.



