OK, boys and girls. Get out this month's PC World, turn to pp. 90-91 and
follow along with me. We are going to review the "35 Top Features" of Windows
95 and compare them to the Mac and OS/2. This post is rather long, and is
*not* meant to start a flame war. I run Mac OS and OS/2 at home, and Windows
NT and OS/2 at work. Further, I run Windows For Workgroups at both locations.

Personally, I've looked forward to Win95 and am just interested in discussing
the "final" product's features, now that it's here (OK, OK, it's not actually
here yet, but MS has started their media campaign proclaiming 8/24 as the date
it will be available, so I think it's a done deal).

Before I continue, I thought I'd post a few notes, so you know the "rules"
under which I'm playing:

* I don't worship at the OS "out of the box" alter. That is, I'm not above
adding 3rd party software (free/shareware and commercial) to make my OS better
for me. I rate an OS as much by the apps for it as anything else, that goes
for utilities, too. This is why I have Now Utilities on my Mac, QwikSwitch on
my OS/2 box, and Norton Desktop on my WfW setup, along with many others.

* I'm running OS/2 Warp for Windows at work, with the FixPack 5 installed.
Also TCP/IP 2.0 with CSD and Netware Client 2.11. Internet access is through
the LAN. At home, I run Warp FullPack with the Internet Access Kit through a
local provider.

* I'm running System 7.1.2 on my Mac. For those of you who don't know, this is
the last release of 7.1 before 7.5 became available last October. Some of the
features I am now getting with 3rd-party utilities come standard on 7.5. I've
just never bothered to upgrade.

* I have *not* use Win95 extensively. I have read extensively on the subject,
however, and have had some "hands on" time on a friend's box. If I get
something wrong about Win95 (or the Mac and OS/2, for that matter) please
correct me, but don't flame (I just ignore flames).

* Because the Top 35 is a Windows 95 list, this discussion is probably
"biased" towards Win95. But I had to start somewhere. Besides, as you'll see,
many of the features are in all three OS'es.

* Finally, everything expressed below is IMHO. Any omissions are by mistake.
It is *not* my intention to decide which OS is "best", but rather to briefly
discuss each OS'es features, starting with the "35 Top Features" of Win95 as
proclaimed by PC World. I don't care who came up with a feature first,
except to the extent that I can claim to have used it and know whether it's
beneficial _for_me_ or not.

Let's get started with the Top 35:

1) Start Button: Mac users will recognize this as the Apple menu. Always
available, very customizable, I consider it a great feature of the Mac OS. I
look forward to having it on my Windows box. OS/2 has the Launchpad, which
isn't quite the same (it's biggest drawback is that it's not heirarchical) but
is also very good.

2) The Desktop: The Mac and OS/2 already have this. Again, it will be great to
have this on my Windows box.

3) Taskbar: This is very nice feature. It's customizable enough that just
about everyone can make it useful for them. Mac users can get an idea of what
it's like by running the Desktop Control Strip with any number of modules that
show an icon for every running app (which is what I do). OS/2 users could run
the Launchpad with small icons and place it at the bottom of the screen so
it's always visible to get some of the same effect (in conjunction with some
other options, OS/2 is very flexibile in this regard). The Taskbar can also
appraise the user of various status conditions, and control the environment
(sound volume, etc.). Again, on the Mac, the control strip does this. OS/2's
Launchpad does not.

4) My Computer: To be honest, I'm not sure *what* to make of this. It's at
once both good and bad, IMO. It lets you browse thorugh your directories, but
also contains info on your installed hardware. To that end, the Mac and OS/2
don't have anything like it. OS/2 could probably use it, but the Mac isn't as
hardware intensive (no IRQ's, DMA's, etc.) and probably doesn't need it.

5) Explorer: A "new" File Manager, it lets you browse heirarchically through
your directory tree (double-click folders to open them, etc.). You can click a
name and type to rename it. For Mac and OS/2 users, this is old hat. But
again, I'm glad to have it on Windows.

6) Find: A pretty robust Find command. IMO, all three OS'es now have very good
methods of finding files. This is good, as it's one of the last things I've
found a CLI better at. Not any more.

7) Help: It's hard for me to get worked up about this. The best help system
I've seen is AppleGuide when done right. Unfortunately, most manufacturers
don't do it right, so it remains to be seen how effective this new help will
be. It looks good, though.

8) Close, Minimize, Maximize: A separate button for each of these now. Mac
users have always had a single-click to close, so it's no big deal. My biggest
problem with the Close button is that it's on the right-hand side of the
window. This is a problem not only because I may accidentally click it instead
of Min or Max, but also because all these years of GUI'ing have taught me to
move the mouse to the left-hand corner to close. It's going to be hard to
unlearn that habit. OS/2 has the best "minimize" features, in that I can
choose to actually minimize the app, or minimize it to a viewer app, or I can
hide it altogether. The Mac doesn't min/max, rather, it "hides" an
application. What I like is that I have my Mac set to hide an application
automatically when I switch to another one. This way, I don't have to perform
two actions, just one.

9) Plug & Play: We all know this. The Mac's got it, Win95 will have it for new
hardware, and OS/2 doesn't yet.

10) Folders: Nothing new to the Mac or OS/2. Glad to see it in Windows.

11) Long File Names: Again, the Mac and OS/2 have this. But the Mac is limited
to 31 characters, while Win95 (and OS/2?) have a limit of 255. Time will tell
whether this 255 character limit will prove useful (I've never used that many
for OS/2). Still, the fewer restrictions, the better, so I'll give the nod to
both OS/2 and Win95 for extending the possibilities here.

12) Microsoft Exchange: This sounds similar to PowerTalk under System 7.5 on
the Mac. I don't know of anything in OS/2 like it.

13) The Microsoft Network: Their very own online service. Apple has eWorld,
which is very ho-hum. I expect MSN to be a lot better. One very nice thing
about MSN is its tight integration into the OS. You can create shortcuts to
places online. I think this is pretty cool. For OS/2, they don't have their
own online service, but their IAK gives great (and easy) internet access.
Their Web browser lets you drag-n-drop URL's, which is also pretty cool. I
think Netscape for Win95 will also allow this.

14) Drag And Drop: All three OS'es have this. The Mac's going so far as to let
me drag apps, files, or folders up to special menus on the menubar for
dropping. I can routinely move a file from the top level of the heirarchy down
to, say, the tenth without opening a single window!

15) Scraps: As desribed, this is identical to a feature on the Mac's System
7.5 whose name escapes me (Mac users chime in). I don't know of anything like
it in OS/2.

16) Shortcuts: Sounds like Aliases on the Mac and Shadows under OS/2. IMO,
OS/2 shadows are the weakest, in that they are strictly WPS items. On the Mac,
an alias is recognized *everywhere*, not just in the finder. For example, I
have a folder on my Mac and OS/2 desktops containing aliases/shadows to my
most commonly used directores. This makes it easy to get to them or copy/move
files there. However, I can also use the Mac's folder when in an application's
Open/Save dialog box, since the aliases are recognized. In OS/2 however, the
shadows do not appear anywhere but in the WPS. One advantage of Shadows,
however, is they are not files, but references in the OS/2 INI files. As such,
they take up no disk space whatsoever. I believe Win95's Shortcuts are more
like Aliases than Shadows. I hope so.

17) Right Mouse Button: Context sensitive menus when you right-click on an
object. I *love* this. It's one of the Mac OS'es biggest mistakes not
to adapt this eminently useful feature.

18) Properties: Gives you information on an object, much of which can be
changed. OS/2 has this as well. The closest thing the Mac has is the Get Info
command, which doesn't tell you enough, IMO. I use Get More Info, myself,
which helps quite a bit.

19) System Properties: According to PC World, this is where you "can display,
diagnose, and configure your system. You may find yourself digging around in
here more than you'd fancy." The Mac's Plug and Play generally makes such
"digging around" unnecessary. But OS/2 could probably use such a beast. It
appears to be one of those features you'll love when you need it, but hope
you'll never need it.

20) Registry: This is where all system and applications settings are kept
(i.e., no more INI files). Windows NT has this and I'm not sure whether I like
it better than text-based INI files or not.

21) Wizards: Special dialogs to walk you through the hard stuff. I think
they're kind of neat, myself. If only because they help bring a little ease to
the otherwise difficult (for most people) task of installing new hardware. It
remains to be seen whether they are helpful enough to make a difference (i.e.,
will someone who couldn't install something before be able to do so now?).
Still, I appreciate the effort thay made and genuinely hope it works.

22) New Utilities: A new Write (WordPad), Terminal (HyperTerminal) and Notepad
app. OS/2 comes with the BonusPack, though, and IBMWORKS and HyperAccess Lite
are much better than WordPad and HyperTerminal. The Mac comes with nothing to
speak of. The verdict: If your needs are relatively light, you can get by
with OS/2's BonusPack. For the Mac and Win 95, you'll need more than what's
included. Personally, I think third-party applications are in your future
for any of the three.

23) Recycle Bin: A very stupid name for what is essentially the Mac's Trash.
Place files there but they aren't actually deleted until you empty it. For
OS/2, you must turn on the undelete function to get files back you've deleted.
But this makes deleting files S-L-O-W!.

24) Briefcase: Allows synching of files, like between a portable and a desktop
machine. OS/2 doesn't come with anything like it. Mac PowerBooks include a
file synchor (sp?).

25) Network Neighborhood: A graphical way to browse and connect to servers on
the network. OS/2 also lets me connect via a nice graphical method. The Mac's
Chooser, by contrast, is weak.

26) Direct Cable Connection: This is between two computers. To my knowledge,
there is third-party software that will let you do this for both Macs and
OS/2. It means nothing to me having it built-in to the OS, but it might to
you.

27) Internet Connectivity: For Win95, this means only TCP/IP and Winsock. For
the Mac, this also means TCP/IP. In both bases, you must supply the apps. For
OS/2, however, this means not only TCP/IP, but a very nice set of apps. The
IAK is really a great thing, IMO, and the best part of the BonusPack.

28) Peer-To-Peer Networking: Actually, Windows has had this since WfW, so it
really isn't new. The Mac has had it even longer, since the original System 7
four (?) years ago. OS/2 has it now in Warp Connect, but that is more
expensive than the other two OS/2 "flavors".

29) Autoplay: For audio CD's, just pop it in and it plays. I have this on my
Mac and OS/2 as well. For non-Audio CD's, it might install itself or
automatically run the program. Non-audio CD's must be written to take
advantage of this, however. I don't know of such a feature on the Mac or OS/2.

30) Tab Dialogs: I'm not sure why this is touted as a Win95 feature. Many
Windows apps already have this. OS/2 has it as well. And so do some Mac
apps. It does help to condese the number of items one needs to open to get at
a feature, however, so it's nice that Win95 will use it system-wide. On the
Mac, it would probably help to cut down the number of separate control panels
needed, which would be useful.

31) Crash Protection: Hey, didn't IBM copyright that term? :-)  This of course
refers to the ever-popular and much bally-hooed Memory Protection. All kidding
aside, it's a great feature to have. My beta of America Online crashes pretty
frequently, but OS/2 just ignores it and moves on, It's great! The Mac doesn't
have this at all, and I can't wait for it to appear. As for Win95, it appears
that all apps (even 32-bit ones) will still share some core memory. It remains
to be seen whether this will really compromise its crash protection or not. I
remain hopeful that it will be quite good, but doubt it can be as good as
OS/2's.

32) Preemptive Multitasking: OS/2's is marvelous. Win95's really needs all
32-bit apps to shine, but is much better than the current Windows. The Mac
doesn't have it. Many Mac users think they don't need it, but I disagree. You
really have to have this feature for a while to appreciate it.

33) Quick View: A built-in file viewer. I like this feature, as it lets you
easily view files if you don't have the app, or maybe you do have the app but
don't want to wait for it to launch. It could use a few more viewers
(something I'm sure third-parties will rush in to supply). I don't know of a
general file viewer for OS/2. Mac users would be best served with Can Opener.

34) Resolution Switching: Lets you change video resolutions (screen size and
number of colors) "on the fly" (no need to reboot). The Mac can do this as
well. For OS/2, you have to reboot.

35) A Better DOS: New commands are available, such as start (like OS/2's?).
I'm sure DOS mavens will notice the difference, but I confess not to. I'm not
much of a command-line kind of guy. In OS/2, I use Yet Another OS/2 Shell and
am quite happy with it. On the Mac, I use a couple of different command lines
just to prove I can do it, but its not as practical there, given the longer
directory names (even with name completion).

Well, that's it. Please comment on anything you like.

